## Migration Analysis

**Three breaking patterns found:**

| Pattern | Location | Issue on .NET 8 |
|---------|----------|-----------------|
| **Blocking call interruption** | `_thread.Interrupt()` in `Stop()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9), unreliable |
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (true)` in `RunLoop()` | No cooperative exit — `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| **Blocking `WaitOne()`** | `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | Cannot be interrupted by cancellation token |

---

### Direct Migration (cooperative cancellation)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new ManualResetEvent(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new Queue<string>();
    private Thread? _thread;
    private readonly object _lock = new object();
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts!.Token;
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny wakes on either a new event OR cancellation
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(
                new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle });

            if (index == 1) // cancellation token was signaled
                break;

            _newEvent.Reset();

            string item;
            lock (_lock) { item = _queue.Dequeue(); }
            Handle(item);
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();        // wakes the thread from WaitAny immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);   // wait for graceful exit
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- `WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _newEvent, token.WaitHandle })` replaces `WaitOne()` — the thread wakes on *either* a new item or cancellation
- `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` replaces `while (true)`
- `_cts.Cancel()` replaces both `Thread.Interrupt()` and `Thread.Abort()`
- `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed in `Stop()`

---

### Recommended Modern Approach (Channel\<T\>)

For .NET 8, `Channel<T>` eliminates the manual lock + queue + event entirely:

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel =
        Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _workerTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Expected on shutdown — don't propagate
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        _channel.Writer.TryWrite(item);
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();
        _cts?.Cancel();
        if (_workerTask is not null)
            await _workerTask.WaitAsync(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

---

### Pitfalls Specific to This Code

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **`WaitOne()` ignores cancellation** | The original `_newEvent.WaitOne()` blocks forever — you *must* use `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` or the thread will never wake on `Stop()` |
| **Race: multiple enqueues, single dequeue** | The original code has a pre-existing bug — multiple `Enqueue` calls before the thread wakes lose the `Set()` signal. `Channel<T>` fixes this automatically |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed** | Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. Always `Dispose()` in `Stop()` |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException` mid-chain** | Only catch it at the top-level loop. Let it propagate everywhere else |
| **`Thread.Abort` after `Join` timeout** | The original fallback "force-kill after 5s" has **no equivalent** in .NET 8. If `Handle(item)` hangs, cooperative cancellation won't help. Pass the token *into* `Handle()` and check it there, or move uncooperative work to a child process |
